{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Conversation Ledger\n2\t\n3\tDurable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in\n4\tyour repository as git notes.\n5\t\n6\t`cledger` (also installed as `conversation-ledger`) is a small standalone\n7\tutility in the unix tradition: it appends immutable JSONL evidence events to\n8\t`refs/notes/conversation-ledger`, anchored to the commit you were on when the\n9\tconversation happened. Records ride the commit DAG — merge a branch and its\n10\tconversations come along — never touch your working tree or `git status`, and\n11\tonly leave your machine when you explicitly `cledger sync`.\n12\t\n13\tConversation Ledger is the neutral foundation of a small ecosystem:\n14\t\n15\t- `conversation-ledger` stores normalized, provenance-preserving conversation evidence.\n16\t- `turnbridge` records and transfers visible conversations between coding CLIs.\n17\t- `intent-recall` later retrieves evidence to help agents reason about original and superseded intent.\n18\t\n19\tThe ledger itself never summarizes, ranks, or interprets. It stores what was\n20\tvisibly said, by whom, against which commit — nothing more.\n21\t\n22\t## Install\n23\t\n24\t```sh\n25\tgit clone https://github.com/evintunador/conversation-ledger\n26\tcd conversation-ledger && npm install && npm link   # npm publish coming later\n27\tcledger install all    # hook capture into Claude Code + Codex CLI\n28\t```\n29\t\n30\t`cledger install` adds `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks to `~/.claude/settings.json`\n31\tand a `Stop` hook (plus `features.hooks = true`) to `~/.codex/config.toml`,\n32\tbacking both up first. From then on, every completed turn in any git\n33\trepository is captured automatically, in the same universal format. Capture is\n34\tidempotent — events are content-derived, so re-scanning a transcript never\n35\tduplicates.\n36\t\n37\tTwo one-time activation notes: Claude Code reads hooks at session start, so\n38\tcapture begins with your next session; Codex requires you to trust new hooks\n39\tinteractively — open `codex`, run `/hooks`, and approve the `cledger hook\n40\tcodex` command once. Missed turns are never lost either way: `cledger capture\n41\t<source> --transcript PATH` backfills any native transcript, idempotently.\n42\t\n43\t## Use\n44\t\n45\t```sh\n46\tcledger log                     # events on the current branch (via commit reachability)\n47\tcledger log --all --json        # every event, as JSONL for jq & friends\n48\tcledger conversations           # sessions touching this branch\n49\tcledger show claude-code:3f9a   # replay one conversation in order\n50\tcledger export > ledger.jsonl   # lossless dump, incl. source-native payloads\n51\tcledger sync                    # explicit opt-in fetch/merge/push of the ledger ref\n52\techo '{\"kind\":\"decision\",...}' | cledger append   # any tool can write events\n53\t```\n54\t\n55\t## Adapters\n56\t\n57\tSupported today (built-in, hook-based, per-turn):\n58\t\n59\t| Source | Trigger | Transcript store | Notes |\n60\t|---|---|---|---|\n61\t| Claude Code CLI | `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks | `~/.claude/projects/*/*.jsonl` | Also covers the VS Code extension and JetBrains plugin (both share `~/.claude/settings.json` hooks and transcripts), and desktop-app local/SSH/WSL sessions. Cloud \"Remote\" sessions and the Cowork tab run server-side — not captured. |\n62\t| Codex CLI | `[[hooks.Stop]]` hooks engine | `~/.codex/sessions/**/rollout-*.jsonl` | Same config + session store is shared by the Codex desktop app and IDE extension, so their local sessions should capture too — but OpenAI has open bugs on the desktop app's config loading, and third-party reports say hooks may not fire from IDE sessions. Treat non-CLI surfaces as best-effort; `cledger capture codex` backfills any rollout file regardless of which surface wrote it. Cloud tasks run server-side — not captured. |\n63\t\n64\tTODO adapters, roughly in order of how ledger-friendly their storage/hook\n65\tstory looks (all have local session stores; most grew Claude-Code-style hook\n66\tsystems):\n67\t\n68\t- **Gemini CLI** — JSON chats under `~/.gemini/tmp/<hash>/chats/`; documented hooks.\n69\t- **Kimi CLI** — `~/.kimi-code/` sessions; Claude-Code-inspired lifecycle hooks.\n70\t- **GitHub Copilot CLI** — `~/.copilot/session-state/`; documented hooks dirs.\n71\t- **Factory droid** — `~/.factory/` sessions; `hooks.json`.\n72\t- **Qwen Code** — `~/.qwen/projects/*/chats/`; hooks system.\n73\t- **opencode** — SQLite under `~/.local/share/opencode/`; plugin-API events rather than shell hooks.\n74\t- **Cursor (`cursor-agent` CLI)** — `~/.cursor/chats`; hooks exist, but IDE-side chats live in editor-internal storage.\n75\t- **aider** — plain `.aider.chat.history.md`; no hook mechanism found, would need file watching.\n76\t- **Goose / Amp** — SQLite store / cloud-synced threads; hook stories unclear or absent.\n77\t\n78\t## Security & redaction\n79\t\n80\tVisible tool output can contain secrets: API keys in error messages, credentials in logs, etc. The trust boundary is transport — native transcripts are plaintext locally, so redaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. Once content reaches a note, removal is expensive, so prevention runs first at capture, with the last checkpoint at sync.\n81\t\n82\t### Redaction layers\n83\t\n84\t**Capture-time redaction** (default on): Replaces prefixed tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`, `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private keys, JWTs with `[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]`. Conservative, near-zero false-positive ruleset applied before event ids are computed.\n85\t- Threat addressed: API tokens and private keys in tool output land in shared history.\n86\t- Cost of disabling: `.cledger.json` `{\"redact\": {\"capture\": false}}` — every secret lands verbatim.\n87\t\n88\t**Custom patterns**: Extend capture rules via `{\"redact\": {\"patterns\": [{\"id\": \"my-rule\", \"pattern\": \"...\"}]}}` in `~/.config/cledger/config.json` (global) or `<repo>/.cledger.json` (repo wins).\n89\t- Threat addressed: domain-specific secrets unmatched by standard rules.\n90\t- Cost: manual configuration required.\n91\t\n92\t**Env-value masking** (opt-in, default off): Scrub exact values of environment variables and `.env` entries via `{\"redact\": {\"env\": true}}`.\n93\t- Threat addressed: unstructured secrets in local config.\n94\t- Cost of enabling: `.env` plain-config values get masked too; machine-dependent (rescans produce duplicate events with different ids).\n95\t\n96\t**Sync-time scan** (default on, tiered): Before any push, scans only new events with medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run, keyword assignments like `password=`, URL credentials). Findings abort the push with a report and remediation instructions.\n97\t- Threat addressed: secrets from older capture rules or new tool formats slipping through.\n98\t- Cost of disabling: `{\"scan\": {\"tier\": \"off\"}}` — secrets in tool output push silently.\n99\t- Remediation paths: `cledger redact <event-id>` (real secrets), `cledger allow <fingerprint>` (false positives), `cledger sync --no-scan` (bypass once). `--paranoid` tier adds entropy-based detection (noisier but broader).\n100\t\n101\t### Commands\n102\t\n103\t`cledger redact <event-id> (--pattern REGEX | --all) [--reason TEXT]`: Rewrites stored event to placeholder + audit metadata, appends a `redaction` event, and squashes local notes history so prior content is unrecoverable (pre-push only; post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built).\n104\t\n105\t`cledger scan [--paranoid]`: Standalone check with exit 1 on findings — CI-friendly.\n106\t\n107\t### Maximum safety recipe\n108\t\n109\tKeep all defaults (capture and sync scan on), add repo-specific patterns in `.cledger.json` for domain-specific secrets, enable env masking only if `.env` holds secrets (not config), run `cledger scan` in CI, and treat `--no-scan` as a deliberate exception you document.\n110\t\n111\t## Roadmap\n112\t\n113\t- **Transport hooks** (decided, unbuilt) — optional-but-default-on `pre-push`\n114\t  git hook running the sync push (scan-gated) plus a staged fetch refspec\n115\t  merged lazily at read time, so the ledger rides normal `git push`/`pull`\n116\t  instead of requiring explicit `cledger sync`.\n117\t- **Path-based capture exclusion** — the path half of the redaction config\n118\t  (\"never record reads of `secrets/**`\"); requires correlating `tool_use`\n119\t  file paths with their `tool_result` events.\n120\t- **Post-push purge** — true content removal after the ledger ref has been\n121\t  shared (force-push + collaborator re-fetch coordination); the local\n122\t  pre-push squash shipped with `cledger redact`.\n123\t- **`re-anchor`** — reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history\n124\t  rewrites. The desired end state is that this happens by default: a squash\n125\t  commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed.\n126\t  Hard part: squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub \"Squash and merge\"),\n127\t  so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local\n128\t  hook.\n129\t- **Harness-artifact capture** — decide whether the ledger should also\n130\t  preserve valuable non-git-controlled agent artifacts that normally die\n131\t  with a worktree or live outside the repo (e.g. Claude Code auto-memory\n132\t  directories, session state). They fit the `document` kind; the question is\n133\t  scope and capture triggers.\n134\t- **Format-drift resilience** — adapters currently skip transcript line\n135\t  types they don't recognize, so a harness update that introduces new\n136\t  message types would silently leave that content uncaptured (see\n137\t  \"Versioning\" in the design doc). At minimum: count and warn about\n138\t  skipped-but-substantive lines; possibly preserve them raw-only.\n139\t- **Purge tooling** — true content removal behind a `redaction` event.\n140\t- **Sub-turn citation anchors** for downstream consumers like intent-recall.\n141\t\n142\t## Storage model, in one paragraph\n143\t\n144\tOne git note per anchor commit under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`; the\n145\tnote body is one canonical-JSON event per line, sorted and unique, with all\n146\tcontent inline (GC-safe, no out-of-repo pointers). Concurrent branches merge\n147\tconflict-free via git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes strategy. Events record\n148\trepository, branch, HEAD, dirty-tree fingerprint, actor, timestamps, and\n149\tcapture mechanism. Redaction appends a `redaction` event rather than silently\n150\trewriting history. See [docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md](docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md)\n151\tfor details and [docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md](docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md) for what this\n152\ttool deliberately refuses to become.\n153\t\n154\t## License\n155\t\n156\t[MIT](LICENSE)\n157\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_01LwwsqDucR9DUDq7MUSSBPY","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","dirty_fingerprint":"dbebfcb12daf57bc85c3fc0e02654fa9ee16601a41776f3fbb378435e3e2d63e","head":"d74e3912b5814be527c90a603d04dfe055562a99","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:6d97a17b-0d4f-459a-8341-06e6be6eb0b0","seq":253},"id":"ev1-26f3e7883ebe8911b7cd7961ecb9a1ead6ea2930676fe6cc6d7c884c455012ed","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T05:58:01.830Z","producer":{"session_id":"6d97a17b-0d4f-459a-8341-06e6be6eb0b0","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.4.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"content":"1\t# Conversation Ledger\n2\t\n3\tDurable, attributable records of visible coding-agent conversations, stored in\n4\tyour repository as git notes.\n5\t\n6\t`cledger` (also install