later retrieves evidence to help agents reason about original and superseded intent.\n\nThe ledger itself never summarizes, ranks, or interprets. It stores what was\nvisibly said, by whom, against which commit — nothing more.\n\n## Install\n\n```sh\ngit clone https://github.com/evintunador/conversation-ledger\ncd conversation-ledger && npm install && npm link   # npm publish coming later\ncledger install all    # hook capture into Claude Code + Codex CLI\n```\n\n`cledger install` adds `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks to `~/.claude/settings.json`\nand a `Stop` hook (plus `features.hooks = true`) to `~/.codex/config.toml`,\nbacking both up first. From then on, every completed turn in any git\nrepository is captured automatically, in the same universal format. Capture is\nidempotent — events are content-derived, so re-scanning a transcript never\nduplicates.\n\nTwo one-time activation notes: Claude Code reads hooks at session start, so\ncapture begins with your next session; Codex requires you to trust new hooks\ninteractively — open `codex`, run `/hooks`, and approve the `cledger hook\ncodex` command once. Missed turns are never lost either way: `cledger capture\n<source> --transcript PATH` backfills any native transcript, idempotently.\n\n## Use\n\n```sh\ncledger log                     # events on the current branch (via commit reachability)\ncledger log --all --json        # every event, as JSONL for jq & friends\ncledger conversations           # sessions touching this branch\ncledger show claude-code:3f9a   # replay one conversation in order\ncledger export > ledger.jsonl   # lossless dump, incl. source-native payloads\ncledger sync                    # explicit opt-in fetch/merge/push of the ledger ref\necho '{\"kind\":\"decision\",...}' | cledger append   # any tool can write events\n```\n\n## Adapters\n\nSupported today (built-in, hook-based, per-turn):\n\n| Source | Trigger | Transcript store | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Claude Code CLI | `Stop`/`SessionEnd` hooks | `~/.claude/projects/*/*.jsonl` | Also covers the VS Code extension and JetBrains plugin (both share `~/.claude/settings.json` hooks and transcripts), and desktop-app local/SSH/WSL sessions. Cloud \"Remote\" sessions and the Cowork tab run server-side — not captured. |\n| Codex CLI | `[[hooks.Stop]]` hooks engine | `~/.codex/sessions/**/rollout-*.jsonl` | Same config + session store is shared by the Codex desktop app and IDE extension, so their local sessions should capture too — but OpenAI has open bugs on the desktop app's config loading, and third-party reports say hooks may not fire from IDE sessions. Treat non-CLI surfaces as best-effort; `cledger capture codex` backfills any rollout file regardless of which surface wrote it. Cloud tasks run server-side — not captured. |\n\nTODO adapters, roughly in order of how ledger-friendly their storage/hook\nstory looks (all have local session stores; most grew Claude-Code-style hook\nsystems):\n\n- **Gemini CLI** — JSON chats under `~/.gemini/tmp/<hash>/chats/`; documented hooks.\n- **Kimi CLI** — `~/.kimi-code/` sessions; Claude-Code-inspired lifecycle hooks.\n- **GitHub Copilot CLI** — `~/.copilot/session-state/`; documented hooks dirs.\n- **Factory droid** — `~/.factory/` sessions; `hooks.json`.\n- **Qwen Code** — `~/.qwen/projects/*/chats/`; hooks system.\n- **opencode** — SQLite under `~/.local/share/opencode/`; plugin-API events rather than shell hooks.\n- **Cursor (`cursor-agent` CLI)** — `~/.cursor/chats`; hooks exist, but IDE-side chats live in editor-internal storage.\n- **aider** — plain `.aider.chat.history.md`; no hook mechanism found, would need file watching.\n- **Goose / Amp** — SQLite store / cloud-synced threads; hook stories unclear or absent.\n\n## Security & redaction\n\nVisible tool output can contain secrets: API keys in error messages, credentials in logs, etc. The trust boundary is transport — native transcripts are plaintext locally, so redaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. Once content reaches a note, removal is expensive, so prevention runs first at capture, with the last checkpoint at sync.\n\n### Redaction layers\n\n**Capture-time redaction** (default on): Replaces prefixed tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`, `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private keys, JWTs with `[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]`. Conservative, near-zero false-positive ruleset applied before event ids are computed.\n- Threat addressed: API tokens and private keys in tool output land in shared history.\n- Cost of disabling: `.cledger.json` `{\"redact\": {\"capture\": false}}` — every secret lands verbatim.\n\n**Custom patterns**: Extend capture rules via `{\"redact\": {\"patterns\": [{\"id\": \"my-rule\", \"pattern\": \"...\"}]}}` in `~/.config/cledger/config.json` (global) or `<repo>/.cledger.json` (repo wins).\n- Threat addressed: domain-specific secrets unmatched by standard rules.\n- Cost: manual configuration required.\n\n**Env-value masking** (opt-in, default off): Scrub exact values of environment variables and `.env` entries via `{\"redact\": {\"env\": true}}`.\n- Threat addressed: unstructured secrets in local config.\n- Cost of enabling: `.env` plain-config values get masked too; machine-dependent (rescans produce duplicate events with different ids).\n\n**Sync-time scan** (default on, tiered): Before any push, scans only new events with medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run, keyword assignments like `password=`, URL credentials). Findings abort the push with a report and remediation instructions.\n- Threat addressed: secrets from older capture rules or new tool formats slipping through.\n- Cost of disabling: `{\"scan\": {\"tier\": \"off\"}}` — secrets in tool output push silently.\n- Remediation paths: `cledger redact <event-id>` (real secrets), `cledger allow <fingerprint>` (false positives), `cledger sync --no-scan` (bypass once). `--paranoid` tier adds entropy-based detection (noisier but broader).\n\n### Commands\n\n`cledger redact <event-id> (--pattern REGEX | --all) [--reason TEXT]`: Rewrites stored event to placeholder + audit metadata, appends a `redaction` event, and squashes local notes history so prior content is unrecoverable (pre-push only; post-push purge tooling is planned, not yet built).\n\n`cledger scan [--paranoid]`: Standalone check with exit 1 on findings — CI-friendly.\n\n### Maximum safety recipe\n\nKeep all defaults (capture and sync scan on), add repo-specific patterns in `.cledger.json` for domain-specific secrets, enable env masking only if `.env` holds secrets (not config), run `cledger scan` in CI, and treat `--no-scan` as a deliberate exception you document.\n\n## Roadmap\n\n- **Transport hooks** (decided, unbuilt) — optional-but-default-on `pre-push`\n  git hook running the sync push (scan-gated) plus a staged fetch refspec\n  merged lazily at read time, so the ledger rides normal `git push`/`pull`\n  instead of requiring explicit `cledger sync`.\n- **Path-based capture exclusion** — the path half of the redaction config\n  (\"never record reads of `secrets/**`\"); requires correlating `tool_use`\n  file paths with their `tool_result` events.\n- **Post-push purge** — true content removal after the ledger ref has been\n  shared (force-push + collaborator re-fetch coordination); the local\n  pre-push squash shipped with `cledger redact`.\n- **`re-anchor`** — reattach events orphaned by squash merges or history\n  rewrites. The desired end state is that this happens by default: a squash\n  commit should end up carrying the conversations of the branch it squashed.\n  Hard part: squashes often happen off-machine (GitHub \"Squash and merge\"),\n  so detection needs patch-id/branch-tip matching after fetch, not a local\n  hook.\n- **Harness-artifact capture** — decide whether the ledger should also\n  preserve valuable non-git-controlled agent artifacts that normally die\n  with a worktree or live outside the repo (e.g. Claude Code auto-memory\n  directories, session state). They fit the `document` kind; the question is\n  scope and capture triggers.\n- **Format-drift resilience** — adapters currently skip transcript line\n  types they don't recognize, so a harness update that introduces new\n  message types would silently leave that content uncaptured (see\n  \"Versioning\" in the design doc). At minimum: count and warn about\n  skipped-but-substantive lines; possibly preserve them raw-only.\n- **Purge tooling** — true content removal behind a `redaction` event.\n- **Sub-turn citation anchors** for downstream consumers like intent-recall.\n\n## Storage model, in one paragraph\n\nOne git note per anchor commit under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`; the\nnote body is one canonical-JSON event per line, sorted and unique, with all\ncontent inline (GC-safe, no out-of-repo pointers). Concurrent branches merge\nconflict-free via git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes strategy. Events record\nrepository, branch, HEAD, dirty-tree fingerprint, actor, timestamps, and\ncapture mechanism. Redaction appends a `redaction` event rather than silently\nrewriting history. See [docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md](docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md)\nfor details and [docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md](docs/PRODUCT_INTENT.md) for what this\ntool deliberately refuses to become.\n\n## License\n\n[MIT](LICENSE)\n","filePath":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/README.md","numLines":157,"startLine":1,"totalLines":157},"type":"text"},"type":"user","userType":"external","uuid":"a992f289-312f-45b8-96ca-8b82b61e0acb","version":"2.1.215"},"format":"claude-code-jsonl/1"},"recorded_at":"2026-07-20T06:00:14.255Z","schema":"conversation-ledger/v1"}
{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Technical design\n2\t\n3\t**Status:** implemented in v0.1; format may still evolve until v1.\n4\t\n5\t## Scope\n6\t\n7\tConversation Ledger defines a canonical append-only event format plus a local,\n8\tgit-backed storage protocol. It preserves exact visible content while staying\n9\tout of the working tree. Transport of the ledger ref is explicit today\n10\t(`cledger sync`); the decided direction is an optional, on-by-default git\n11\tpre-push hook plus fetch refspec so records propagate with normal git use\n12\t(see open questions).\n13\t\n14\t## Canonical objects\n15\t\n16\tAn `EvidenceEvent` is immutable and has:\n17\t\n18\t- `id`: `ev1-` + sha256 of the event's *identity subset* — the durable,\n19\t  source-determined fields (`kind`, `occurred_at`, `actor.type/id`,\n20\t  `producer.source/session_id`, `conversation`, `media_type`, `content`,\n21\t  `links`). Volatile provenance (`recorded_at`, `context`, `raw`,\n22\t  `producer.tool/version`) is excluded, so re-scanning the same source\n23\t  material always yields the same id: capture is idempotent by construction,\n24\t  and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable.\n25\t- `schema` version (`conversation-ledger/v1`);\n26\t- `kind`: `conversation_turn`, `decision`, `document`, `annotation`,\n27\t  `redaction`, or `supersession` — an open string; unknown kinds are stored\n28\t  verbatim so downstream tools can extend without a schema release;\n29\t- `occurred_at` (from the source) and `recorded_at` (at append) timestamps;\n30\t- `actor` (human/agent/system + identity) and `producer` (capture tool,\n31\t  source system, native session id) provenance; adapters stamp human turns\n32\t  with the repo's `git config user.email`/`user.name` (`actor.id`/`.display`)\n33\t  so multi-user clients can filter by author. Because `actor.id` is part of\n34\t  the event identity subset, sessions captured before this stamping existed\n35\t  will produce new event ids if fully re-scanned — the per-session cursor\n36\t  normally prevents that, but a forced rescan can duplicate pre-identity\n37\t  turns;\n38\t- `content`, stored inline, with an optional `media_type`\n39\t  (default `application/json`);\n40\t- `context`: repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a\n41\t  dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`);\n42\t- `conversation`: namespaced id (`claude-code:<session>`) plus a stable\n43\t  `seq` (source line index) providing conversation ordering — the manifest is\n44\t  currently implicit in these fields rather than a separate object;\n45\t- optional `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`, `annotates`, ...).\n46\t\n47\tConversation turns preserve visible roles, text, tool calls, and tool results\n48\tas supplied by their capture adapter. The source-native payload is retained\n49\tunder `raw` as an opaque, versioned attachment for lossless export.\n50\t\n51\tReasoning policy: record model reasoning when the provider exposes it\n52\t(Claude Code's thinking text is kept, minus opaque signatures); never chase\n53\tit when the provider withholds it (Codex's encrypted `reasoning` payloads\n54\tare skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed).\n55\t\n56\t## Storage\n57\t\n58\tOne git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\n59\tThe note body is JSONL: one canonical-JSON (sorted-keys) event per line,\n60\tlexicographically sorted, unique.\n61\t\n62\tWhy this shape:\n63\t\n64\t1. **Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time,\n65\t   so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits —\n66\t   and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with\n67\t   no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via\n68\t   `git rev-list` reachability.\n69\t2. **GC-safe, nothing outside git.** All content lives inline in the note\n70\t   blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to\n71\t   stores outside the repository.\n72\t3. **Conflict-free concurrency.** Deterministic serialization + sorted unique\n73\t   lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy (configured per-ref\n74\t   at first append) unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism\n75\t   git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\n76\t4. **Clean working tree.** Notes never appear in `git status`; sharing is a\n77\t   `cledger sync` (fetch → `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` → push) of\n78\t   that single ref — explicit-only today, with an optional on-by-default\n79\t   pre-push hook planned so it rides normal `git push` (still\n80\t   user-disableable; the E scan gates it either way).\n81\t\n82\tEvents captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n83\t`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\n84\tanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\n85\tcursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n86\t\n87\t### Known limitation: squash merges\n88\t\n89\tA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\n90\tremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n91\t`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\n92\treachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n93\t\n94\t## Capture adapters\n95\t\n96\t`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n97\t(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n98\t(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n99\t`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\n100\trepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\n101\tidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n102\t`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n103\t\n104\t## Privacy and integrity\n105\t\n106\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\n107\tnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\n108\tredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\n109\tsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\n110\tretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\n111\tcheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\n112\tmutation detectable.\n113\t\n114\t### Redaction layers\n115\t\n116\tDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do:\n117\t\n118\t- **A. Capture-time pattern redaction (default on).** A deliberately\n119\t  conservative, versioned ruleset of unambiguous secret formats — prefixed\n120\t  API tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`,\n121\t  `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private-key blocks, JWTs — applied to every\n122\t  draft inside `appendEvents`, before ids are computed. Matches in both\n123\t  `content` and `raw.data` are replaced with a deterministic placeholder\n124\t  (see below). No entropy heuristics here: a false positive silently\n125\t  rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment, so\n126\t  capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction.\n127\t- **B. External scanners as test oracle only.** gitleaks/trufflehog-class\n128\t  rulesets are used in the test suite to prove the capture tier catches\n129\t  what it claims (secret corpus in, zero findings out) — never vendored\n130\t  into the runtime path.\n131\t- **C. Env-value masking (opt-in, default off).** Scrub exact values of\n132\t  local environment variables / `.env` entries from captured content.\n133\t  Highest recall for unstructured secrets, but `.env` is often plain\n134\t  config, and the transform depends on machine state — so it is\n135\t  nondeterministic across rescans (id churn is the documented cost of\n136\t  opting in).\n137\t- **D. User pattern rules (config).** Extra redaction regexes merged into\n138\t  the capture tier from config. Path-based exclusion (\"never record reads\n139\t  of `secrets/**`\") is planned; it requires correlating `tool_use` inputs\n140\t  with `tool_result` events and is not in v1.\n141\t- **E. Sync-time scan (default on, tiered).** Before push, scan only the\n142\t  events the remote does not yet have. The default profile runs\n143\t  medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run for events captured\n144\t  under older rules, keyword-anchored assignments, URL credentials); on a\n145\t  hit the push blocks with an interactive finding report — allowlist the\n146\t  false positive (persisted by fingerprint) or `cledger redact` the real\n147\t  secret while purge is still a local operation. Entropy heuristics live\n148\t  behind an opt-in paranoid tier; `--no-scan`/config disables the gate\n149\t  entirely. Scan-tier rules may be noisy precisely because they only warn\n150\t  a human — they never rewrite anything.\n151\t\n152\t### Redaction metadata\n153\t\n154\tA capture-time redaction replaces the matched span with\n155\t`[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` — fingerprint is a truncated\n156\t`sha256(secret)`, letting identical secrets correlate across events without\n157\tbeing recoverable (brute-forceable only for low-entropy values, which the\n158\tcapture tier does not target). The event also carries a `redactions` array\n159\t(rule id, ruleset version, fingerprint, location path); it sits outside the\n160\tidentity subset, since the rewritten `content` already determines the id.\n161\tDeterminism rule: capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source\n162\tcontent + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events. Ruleset upgrades\n163\ttherefore change ids on forced rescan — same accepted caveat as identity\n164\tstamping; cursors prevent it in normal operation.\n165\t\n166\tA human redaction of an *existing* event (the E flow) instead rewrites the\n167\tnote line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`,\n168\tthen squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable —\n169\thonest history without secret retention. Post-push purge (force-push +\n170\tcollaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling.\n171\t\n172\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n173\t\n174\tThree layers exist today:\n175\t\n176\t1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n177\t   own envelope.\n178\t2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/1`) versions\n179\t   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n180\t   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n181\t   parser produced an event.\n182\t3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n183\t   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n184\t   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n185\t   newer mapping without recapture.\n186\t\n187\tWhat does not exist yet: drift detection. Adapters are tolerant parsers that\n188\tskip unrecognized line types, which handles additive upstream changes\n189\tgracefully but means a genuinely new message type is dropped entirely (raw\n190\tincluded — only converted lines are stored). See the format-drift roadmap\n191\titem.\n192\t\n193\t## Open questions\n194\t\n195\t- Transport hooks (decided, unbuilt): optional-but-default-on `pre-push`\n196\t  git hook running the sync push (with the E gate), and a staged fetch\n197\t  refspec (`+refs/notes/conversation-ledger:refs/notes/cledger-incoming`)\n198\t  merged lazily at read time — never force-overwriting the local ref.\n199\t  Amends the \"sharing is explicit\" commitment here and in Turnbridge's\n200\t  product intent.\n201\t- Path-based capture exclusion (the path half of layer D): requires\n202\t  correlating tool_use file paths with their tool_result events.\n203\t- Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator\n204\t  re-fetch coordination).\n205\t- Unset `git config user.email` leaves human turns unattributed\n206\t  (`gitUserIdentity` returns null; common on fresh machines/containers).\n207\t  Planned fix: fall back to git's *effective* author identity so\n208\t  `actor.id` matches commit authorship, and have `cledger install` warn\n209\t  when user.email is unset. Hostname/OS-username anchors are ruled out —\n210\t  they churn (DHCP renames) and would churn event ids.\n211\t- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n212\t- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n213\t  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n214\t  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n215\t  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n216\t- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n217\t  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n218\t- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n219\t  multiple producers exist.\n220\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_01VPnVfAVVzUT6TTxxXQcuz2","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","dirty_fingerprint":"dbebfcb12daf57bc85c3fc0e02654fa9ee16601a41776f3fbb378435e3e2d63e","head":"d74e3912b5814be527c90a603d04dfe055562a99","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:6d97a17b-0d4f-459a-8341-06e6be6eb0b0","seq":15},"id":"ev1-ae54c351ac174250667792542749c22fa4b8bdfc806ccad9b4d2f38d09e6a689","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T05:31:38.087Z","producer":{"session_id":"6d97a17b-0d4f-459a-8341-06e6be6eb0b0","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.4.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isS