 (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\nanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\ncursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n\n### Known limitation: squash merges\n\nA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\nremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\nreachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n\n## Capture adapters\n\n`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\nrepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\nidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n\n## Privacy and integrity\n\nVisible tool output can contain secrets. The trust boundary is transport:\nnative transcripts already sit in plaintext on the capturing machine, so\nredaction protects the *shared* record, not the local disk. But once a\nsecret reaches a note, removal is expensive (the notes ref's own history\nretains prior blobs), so prevention layers run at capture and the last\ncheckpoint runs at sync. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental\nmutation detectable.\n\n### Redaction layers\n\nDefense in depth, ordered by where they run and what they may do:\n\n- **A. Capture-time pattern redaction (default on).** A deliberately\n  conservative, versioned ruleset of unambiguous secret formats — prefixed\n  API tokens (`ghp_…`, `sk-ant-…`, `AKIA…`, `xox…-`, `AIza…`, `glpat-…`,\n  `npm_…`, `sk_live_…`), PEM private-key blocks, JWTs — applied to every\n  draft inside `appendEvents`, before ids are computed. Matches in both\n  `content` and `raw.data` are replaced with a deterministic placeholder\n  (see below). No entropy heuristics here: a false positive silently\n  rewrites the record, which violates the preservation commitment, so\n  capture-tier rules must be near-zero-false-positive by construction.\n- **B. External scanners as test oracle only.** gitleaks/trufflehog-class\n  rulesets are used in the test suite to prove the capture tier catches\n  what it claims (secret corpus in, zero findings out) — never vendored\n  into the runtime path.\n- **C. Env-value masking (opt-in, default off).** Scrub exact values of\n  local environment variables / `.env` entries from captured content.\n  Highest recall for unstructured secrets, but `.env` is often plain\n  config, and the transform depends on machine state — so it is\n  nondeterministic across rescans (id churn is the documented cost of\n  opting in).\n- **D. User pattern rules (config).** Extra redaction regexes merged into\n  the capture tier from config. Path-based exclusion (\"never record reads\n  of `secrets/**`\") is planned; it requires correlating `tool_use` inputs\n  with `tool_result` events and is not in v1.\n- **E. Sync-time scan (default on, tiered).** Before push, scan only the\n  events the remote does not yet have. The default profile runs\n  medium/high-precision rules (capture ruleset re-run for events captured\n  under older rules, keyword-anchored assignments, URL credentials); on a\n  hit the push blocks with an interactive finding report — allowlist the\n  false positive (persisted by fingerprint) or `cledger redact` the real\n  secret while purge is still a local operation. Entropy heuristics live\n  behind an opt-in paranoid tier; `--no-scan`/config disables the gate\n  entirely. Scan-tier rules may be noisy precisely because they only warn\n  a human — they never rewrite anything.\n\n### Redaction metadata\n\nA capture-time redaction replaces the matched span with\n`[REDACTED:<rule-id>:<fingerprint>]` — fingerprint is a truncated\n`sha256(secret)`, letting identical secrets correlate across events without\nbeing recoverable (brute-forceable only for low-entropy values, which the\ncapture tier does not target). The event also carries a `redactions` array\n(rule id, ruleset version, fingerprint, location path); it sits outside the\nidentity subset, since the rewritten `content` already determines the id.\nDeterminism rule: capture-tier redaction must be a pure function of source\ncontent + versioned ruleset, or rescans duplicate events. Ruleset upgrades\ntherefore change ids on forced rescan — same accepted caveat as identity\nstamping; cursors prevent it in normal operation.\n\nA human redaction of an *existing* event (the E flow) instead rewrites the\nnote line and appends a companion `redaction` event with `links.redacts`,\nthen squashes the local notes ref so the prior blob is unreachable —\nhonest history without secret retention. Post-push purge (force-push +\ncollaborator coordination) is deliberately separate, deferred tooling.\n\n## Versioning against harness format changes\n\nThree layers exist today:\n\n1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n   own envelope.\n2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/1`) versions\n   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n   parser produced an event.\n3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n   newer mapping without recapture.\n\nWhat does not exist yet: drift detection. Adapters are tolerant parsers that\nskip unrecognized line types, which handles additive upstream changes\ngracefully but means a genuinely new message type is dropped entirely (raw\nincluded — only converted lines are stored). See the format-drift roadmap\nitem.\n\n## Open questions\n\n- Transport hooks (decided, unbuilt): optional-but-default-on `pre-push`\n  git hook running the sync push (with the E gate), and a staged fetch\n  refspec (`+refs/notes/conversation-ledger:refs/notes/cledger-incoming`)\n  merged lazily at read time — never force-overwriting the local ref.\n  Amends the \"sharing is explicit\" commitment here and in Turnbridge's\n  product intent.\n- Path-based capture exclusion (the path half of layer D): requires\n  correlating tool_use file paths with their tool_result events.\n- Post-push purge tooling (force-push the notes ref + collaborator\n  re-fetch coordination).\n- Unset `git config user.email` leaves human turns unattributed\n  (`gitUserIdentity` returns null; common on fresh machines/containers).\n  Planned fix: fall back to git's *effective* author identity so\n  `actor.id` matches commit authorship, and have `cledger install` warn\n  when user.email is unset. Hostname/OS-username anchors are ruled out —\n  they churn (DHCP renames) and would churn event ids.\n- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n  multiple producers exist.\n","filePath":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md","numLines":220,"startLine":1,"totalLines":220},"type":"text"},"type":"user","userType":"external","uuid":"6e29470f-d8dc-4119-b71c-4cc14bec3bd3","version":"2.1.215"},"format":"claude-code-jsonl/1"},"recorded_at":"2026-07-20T06:00:14.246Z","schema":"conversation-ledger/v1"}
{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t#!/usr/bin/env node\n2\timport { readFileSync } from \"node:fs\";\n3\timport { stdin as input } from \"node:process\";\n4\timport { findRepo, type RepoInfo } from \"./git.js\";\n5\timport {\n6\t  appendEvents,\n7\t  readEvents,\n8\t  redactEvent,\n9\t  sortEvents,\n10\t  sync,\n11\t  type ReadOptions,\n12\t} from \"./store.js\";\n13\timport { parseEventLine, type EventDraft, type EvidenceEvent } from \"./schema.js\";\n14\timport { runClaudeCodeHook, captureClaudeTranscript } from \"./adapters/claude-code.js\";\n15\timport { runCodexHook, captureCodexTranscript } from \"./adapters/codex.js\";\n16\timport { installAdapters } from \"./install.js\";\n17\timport {\n18\t  addToAllowlist,\n19\t  filterFindings,\n20\t  formatFinding,\n21\t  loadAllowlist,\n22\t  scanEvents,\n23\t} from \"./redact/scan.js\";\n24\t\n25\tconst USAGE = `conversation-ledger — durable records of coding-agent conversations, in git notes\n26\t\n27\tUsage:\n28\t  cledger append [--quiet]                 append JSONL events/drafts from stdin\n29\t  cledger log [--all|--rev R] [--kind K] [--source S] [--conversation C] [--json]\n30\t  cledger show <conversation-id-prefix> [--json]\n31\t  cledger conversations [--rev R]         list conversations on current branch (--all for every branch)\n32\t  cledger export [--rev R]                lossless JSONL dump (default: everything)\n33\t  cledger sync [--remote R] [--push|--fetch] [--no-scan] [--paranoid]\n34\t                                           explicit opt-in fetch/merge/push of the ledger ref;\n35\t                                           push is gated by a secret scan unless --no-scan\n36\t  cledger scan [--all|--rev R] [--paranoid]   scan local events for potential secrets (CI-friendly:\n37\t                                           exits 1 if any finding, 0 otherwise); default scope is\n38\t                                           every local event, --rev restricts by reachability\n39\t  cledger allow <fingerprint...>          mark scan finding fingerprint(s) as known false positives\n40\t  cledger redact <event-id-prefix> (--pattern REGEX | --all) [--reason TEXT]\n41\t                                           rewrite an existing event to remove a secret, keeping its\n42\t                                           id stable, and squash local notes history if unpushed\n43\t  cledger install <claude-code|codex|all>  hook capture into coding CLIs (global)\n44\t  cledger hook <claude-code>              capture entrypoint invoked by CLI hooks (stdin: hook payload)\n45\t  cledger capture <claude-code|codex> --transcript PATH   manual/backfill ingestion\n46\t  cledger --version | --help\n47\t\n48\tEvents are anchored to the HEAD commit at capture time and stored under\n49\trefs/notes/conversation-ledger, so they follow branches through merges and\n50\tsync only when you say so.`;\n51\t\n52\tfunction version(): string {\n53\t  const pkg = JSON.parse(\n54\t    readFileSync(new URL(\"../package.json\", import.meta.url), \"utf8\"),\n55\t  ) as { version: string };\n56\t  return pkg.version;\n57\t}\n58\t\n59\tinterface Flags {\n60\t  [key: string]: string | boolean;\n61\t}\n62\t\n63\tfunction parseArgs(argv: string[]): { positional: string[]; flags: Flags } {\n64\t  const positional: string[] = [];\n65\t  const flags: Flags = {};\n66\t  for (let i = 0; i < argv.length; i++) {\n67\t    const arg = argv[i]!;\n68\t    if (arg.startsWith(\"--\")) {\n69\t      const name = arg.slice(2);\n70\t      const next = argv[i + 1];\n71\t      if (next !== undefined && !next.startsWith(\"--\")) {\n72\t        flags[name] = next;\n73\t        i++;\n74\t      } else {\n75\t        flags[name] = true;\n76\t      }\n77\t    } else {\n78\t      positional.push(arg);\n79\t    }\n80\t  }\n81\t  return { positional, flags };\n82\t}\n83\t\n84\tasync function requireRepo(): Promise<RepoInfo> {\n85\t  const repo = await findRepo(process.cwd());\n86\t  if (!repo) {\n87\t    process.stderr.write(\"cledger: not inside a git repository\\n\");\n88\t    process.exit(2);\n89\t  }\n90\t  return repo;\n91\t}\n92\t\n93\tasync function readStdin(): Promise<string> {\n94\t  const chunks: Buffer[] = [];\n95\t  for await (const chunk of input) chunks.push(chunk as Buffer);\n96\t  return Buffer.concat(chunks).toString(\"utf8\");\n97\t}\n98\t\n99\tfunction readOptionsFrom(flags: Flags): ReadOptions {\n100\t  const opts: ReadOptions = {};\n101\t  if (!flags[\"all\"]) opts.reachableFrom = typeof flags[\"rev\"] === \"string\" ? flags[\"rev\"] : \"HEAD\";\n102\t  if (typeof flags[\"kind\"] === \"string\") opts.kind = flags[\"kind\"];\n103\t  if (typeof flags[\"source\"] === \"string\") opts.source = flags[\"source\"];\n104\t  if (typeof flags[\"conversation\"] === \"string\") opts.conversation = flags[\"conversation\"];\n105\t  return opts;\n106\t}\n107\t\n108\tfunction snippet(event: EvidenceEvent): string {\n109\t  const c = event.content as Record<string, unknown> | string | null;\n110\t  let text = \"\";\n111\t  if (typeof c === \"string\") text = c;\n112\t  else if (c && typeof c === \"object\") {\n113\t    text = String(c[\"text\"] ?? c[\"summary\"] ?? c[\"title\"] ?? JSON.stringify(c));\n114\t  }\n115\t  text = text.replace(/\\s+/g, \" \").trim();\n116\t  return text.length > 100 ? text.slice(0, 97) + \"...\" : text;\n117\t}\n118\t\n119\tfunction printHuman(events: EvidenceEvent[]): void {\n120\t  for (const e of events) {\n121\t    const conv = e.conversation ? `${e.conversation.id.slice(0, 28)}#${e.conversation.seq}` : \"-\";\n122\t    const role =\n123\t      (e.content as Record<string, unknown> | null | undefined) &&\n124\t      typeof e.content === \"object\"\n125\t        ? String((e.content as Record<string, unknown>)[\"role\"] ?? e.actor.type)\n126\t        : e.actor.type;\n127\t    process.stdout.write(\n128\t      `${e.occurred_at}  ${e.kind}  ${role.padEnd(9)}  ${conv}  ${snippet(e)}\\n`,\n129\t    );\n130\t  }\n131\t}\n132\t\n133\tfunction printJsonl(events: EvidenceEvent[], includeRaw: boolean): void {\n134\t  for (const e of events) {\n135\t    const out = includeRaw ? e : { ...e, raw: undefined };\n136\t    process.stdout.write(JSON.stringify(out) + \"\\n\");\n137\t  }\n138\t}\n139\t\n140\tasync function cmdAppend(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n141\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n142\t  const body = await readStdin();\n143\t  const drafts: EventDraft[] = body\n144\t    .split(\"\\n\")\n145\t    .filter((l) => l.trim())\n146\t    .map((l) => JSON.parse(l) as EventDraft);\n147\t  if (drafts.length === 0) return;\n148\t  const result = await appendEvents(repo, drafts);\n149\t  if (!flags[\"quiet\"]) {\n150\t    for (const e of result.appended) process.stdout.write(e.id + \"\\n\");\n151\t    process.stderr.write(\n152\t      `appended ${result.appended.length}, deduped ${result.deduped}` +\n153\t        (result.anchor ? ` (anchor ${result.anchor.slice(0, 12)})` : \" (pending: no commits yet)\") +\n154\t        \"\\n\",\n155\t    );\n156\t  }\n157\t}\n158\t\n159\tasync function cmdLog(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n160\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n161\t  const events = await readEvents(repo, readOptionsFrom(flags));\n162\t  if (flags[\"json\"]) printJsonl(events, false);\n163\t  else printHuman(events);\n164\t}\n165\t\n166\tasync function cmdShow(positional: string[], flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n167\t  const prefix = positional[0];\n168\t  if (!prefix) {\n169\t    process.stderr.write(\"usage: cledger show <conversation-id-prefix>\\n\");\n170\t    process.exit(2);\n171\t  }\n172\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n173\t  const events = await readEvents(repo, { conversation: prefix });\n174\t  if (events.length === 0) {\n175\t    process.stderr.write(`no events for conversation ${prefix}\\n`);\n176\t    process.exit(1);\n177\t  }\n178\t  if (flags[\"json\"]) {\n179\t    printJsonl(events, true);\n180\t    return;\n181\t  }\n182\t  for (const e of sortEvents(events)) {\n183\t    const c = e.content as Record<string, unknown>;\n184\t    const role = typeof c === \"object\" && c ? String(c[\"role\"] ?? e.actor.type) : e.actor.type;\n185\t    const text =\n186\t      typeof c === \"object\" && c && typeof c[\"text\"] === \"string\"\n187\t        ? (c[\"text\"] as string)\n188\t        : JSON.stringify(e.content, null, 2);\n189\t    process.stdout.write(`\\n[${e.occurred_at}] ${role} (${e.kind}, ${e.id.slice(0, 16)})\\n`);\n190\t    process.stdout.write(text.trimEnd() + \"\\n\");\n191\t  }\n192\t}\n193\t\n194\tasync function cmdConversations(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n195\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n196\t  const events = await readEvents(repo, readOptionsFrom(flags));\n197\t  const byConv = new Map<string, { count: number; first: string; last: string; source: string }>();\n198\t  for (const e of events) {\n199\t    const id = e.conversation?.id ?? \"(none)\";\n200\t    const entry = byConv.get(id) ?? {\n201\t      count: 0,\n202\t      first: e.occurred_at,\n203\t      last: e.occurred_at,\n204\t      source: e.producer.source ?? e.producer.tool,\n205\t    };\n206\t    entry.count++;\n207\t    if (e.occurred_at < entry.first) entry.first = e.occurred_at;\n208\t    if (e.occurred_at > entry.last) entry.last = e.occurred_at;\n209\t    byConv.set(id, entry);\n210\t  }\n211\t  for (const [id, s] of [...byConv.entries()].sort((a, b) => a[1].last.localeCompare(b[1].last))) {\n212\t    process.stdout.write(`${id}  ${s.source}  ${s.count} events  ${s.first} .. ${s.last}\\n`);\n213\t  }\n214\t}\n215\t\n216\tasync function cmdExport(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n217\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n218\t  const opts: ReadOptions = {};\n219\t  if (typeof flags[\"rev\"] === \"string\") opts.reachableFrom = flags[\"rev\"];\n220\t  const events = await readEvents(repo, opts);\n221\t  printJsonl(events, true);\n222\t}\n223\t\n224\tasync function cmdSync(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n225\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n226\t  const remote = typeof flags[\"remote\"] === \"string\" ? flags[\"remote\"] : \"origin\";\n227\t  const mode = flags[\"push\"] ? \"push\" : flags[\"fetch\"] ? \"fetch\" : \"both\";\n228\t  const result = await sync(repo, remote, mode, {\n229\t    skipScan: flags[\"no-scan\"] === true,\n230\t    paranoid: flags[\"paranoid\"] === true,\n231\t  });\n232\t  process.stderr.write(\n233\t    `sync ${remote}: ${result.fetched ? \"fetched+merged\" : \"nothing fetched\"}, ` +\n234\t      `${result.pushed ? \"pushed\" : \"not pushed\"}\\n`,\n235\t  );\n236\t}\n237\t\n238\tasync function cmdScan(flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n239\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n240\t  const tier: \"standard\" | \"paranoid\" = flags[\"paranoid\"] ? \"paranoid\" : \"standard\";\n241\t  const opts: ReadOptions = {};\n242\t  if (typeof flags[\"rev\"] === \"string\") opts.reachableFrom = flags[\"rev\"];\n243\t  const events = await readEvents(repo, opts);\n244\t  const findings = filterFindings(scanEvents(events, tier), await loadAllowlist(repo));\n245\t  if (findings.length === 0) {\n246\t    process.stderr.write(\"cledger scan: no findings\\n\");\n247\t    return;\n248\t  }\n249\t  for (const f of findings) process.stdout.write(formatFinding(f) + \"\\n\");\n250\t  process.stderr.write(`cledger scan: ${findings.length} finding(s)\\n`);\n251\t  process.exit(1);\n252\t}\n253\t\n254\tasync function cmdAllow(positional: string[]): Promise<void> {\n255\t  if (positional.length === 0) {\n256\t    process.stderr.write(\"usage: cledger allow <fingerprint...>\\n\");\n257\t    process.exit(2);\n258\t  }\n259\t  const repo = await requireRepo();\n260\t  await addToAllowlist(repo, positional);\n261\t  process.stderr.write(`allowlisted ${positional.length} fingerprint(s)\\n`);\n262\t}\n263\t\n264\tasync function cmdRedact(positional: string[], flags: Flags): Promise<void> {\n265\t  const idPrefix = positional[0];\n266\t  if (!idPrefix) {\n267\t    process.stderr.write(\"usage: cledger redact <event-id-prefix>